  "text": "Firefox multi-process (Fission) architecture content process lifecycle is managed through four key classes in the dom/ipc/ directory:\n\n1. **ContentParent** (dom/ipc/ContentParent.h/.cpp): The parent-side content process manager that implements the PContentParent protocol. ContentParent is a final class that inherits from PContentParent and manages the lifecycle of a single content process, handling IPC communication, resource allocation, and process synchronization.\n\n2. **ContentProcessManager** (dom/ipc/ContentProcessManager.h/.cpp): A singleton registry that tracks all active content processes and browser tabs. It maintains hash maps of ContentParent and BrowserParent instances, providing lookup methods like GetContentProcessById() and GetBrowserParentByProcessAndTabId() to facilitate process and tab management.\n\n3. **BrowserParent** (dom/ipc/BrowserParent.h/.cpp): The parent-side tab representation that implements the PBrowserParent protocol. BrowserParent manages individual tabs within a content process, handling tab-specific IPC messages, rendering, input events, and tab lifecycle.\n\n4. **PreallocatedProcessManager** (dom/ipc/PreallocatedProcessManager.h/.cpp): Manages a pool of preallocated content processes that are created in advance to reduce latency when new tabs or windows are opened. It responds to the dom.ipc.processPrelaunch.enabled preference and maintains the lifecycle of standby processes.\n\nTogether, these classes form the backbone of Firefox's multi-process architecture: PreallocatedProcessManager provides ready processes, ContentParent manages individual processes, BrowserParent manages tabs within processes, and ContentProcessManager coordinates all active processes and tabs in the system."
